@article{Garces2004,
abstract = {PAGES 433,440-441 The rumble of hypersonic objects tearing through the atmosphere can be routinely detected by sensitive infrasound sensors [Brown et al., 2002]. Meteors and reentering spacecraft are the most common hypersonic sources, although supersonic aircraft generate comparable sig­ natures. This article concentrates on two excep­ tionally energetic events: the tragic Columbia reentry of 1 February 2003 (STS-107) and the 23 April 2001 superbolide explosion. On 23 April 2001, a large meteor exploded at a height of -28.5 km between Hawaii and Cali­ fornia. With an estimated explosive energy of -10 k of TNT, this event catalyzed the U.S. infra­ sound community to work with other sectors of government, academia, and industry to provide rapid analyses of any available infrasound, seismic, hydroacoustic, and satellite data that would help identify the explosion source and determine its location. As a result of the precedent for interdiscipli­ nary collaboration established after the 23 April event, on 1 February 2003, the infrasound community was able to respond rapidly and efficiently to the Columbia disaster.The North American infrasound network (Figure 1) detected the Columbia reentry from the coast of Cali­ fornia to its tragic demise over Texas, and provided additional information to government agencies during their interdisciplinary forensic analyses. U.S. stations IS53, IS56, IS57, and IS59 and Canadian station IS 10 are also part of the International Monitoring System (IMS). All infrasound stations of interest here are com­ posed of multiple sensors designed to permit an estimate of the arrival azimuth and apparent propagation speed of a signal across an array Infrasonic signals can be generated in three ways by a hypersonic source.The passage may be recorded as a bow shock with a typical N-wave signature by stations located near the trajectory (Figure 2). Acceleration associated with changes in trajectory can generate addi­ tional shock structure. And lastly a catastrophic explosion can transform substantial kinetic energy into acoustic energy. All of these processes can trap energy into acoustic corridors between the ground and the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, and thermosphere, which may guide infrasonic waves through the atmosphere as they refract at high-velocity zones and reflect from the Earth's surface. Such waveguides permit sound propagation to ranges of thousands of kilome­ ters. Accurate location and identification of distant acoustic sources in the atmosphere strongly depends on an understanding of the propagation path of the observed sound waves.},
