@incollection{Johnson2019,
abstract = {jeffreybjohnson@boisestate.edu 4 208 971 5832 5 6 Submitted as potential chapter for 2 nd ed. Infrasound Monitoring for Atmospheric Studies 7 8 Abstract 9 Infrasound monitoring is employed to enhance understanding of eruption dynamics and 10 to track eruptive activity over time. Local infrasound, where sensors are positioned near 11 to and/or on the flanks of volcanoes, implies that sound transmission from vent to 12 receiver is approximately line-of-sight. Typical assumptions are that pressure decays as 13 the inverse of distance and that attenuation and dispersion effects are minimal. Locally-14 recorded signals thus represent relatively undistorted source-time motions and can be 15 used to effectively characterize volcanic activity. Local monitoring can entail a spectrum 16 of installation topologies including single isolated sensors on a volcano, networks of 17 sensors, a single array, or networks of sensor arrays. Stations may be installed as stand-18 alone or in telemetered configurations depending upon available resources and research 19 objectives, which may range from simple explosion counting to degassing detection, 20 mapping of vents, or identification of moving sources. Some of these objectives are only 21 possible using arrays. Quantifying volcano infrasound, in terms of both spectral shape, 22 power, and signal envelope, is relatively straightforward using data recorded at local 23 distances. Despite inter-network variability, influenced by potential source directivity, 24 propagation effects, and/or site response, the local infrasound records permit good 25 estimation of total acoustic energy, identification of dominant spectral tones, and signal 26 morphology. These parameters may be robustly compared at a volcano over time and/or 27 compared to other volcanoes. Ultimately, infrasound analysis permits remote 28 surveillance of activity occurring at the vent (or on the slopes) of a volcano that may 29 otherwise be difficult to observe. 30